  "text": "We next treated mice with an αLAG-3 antibody to determine whether any differences in clone 4 CD8 + cell expansion could be detected in vivo. As described previously, the monoclonal αLAG-3 antibody does not lead to deletion of LAG-3-expressing T cells [CITATION_1] and is thought to function by blocking LAG-3 interactions with MHC class II [CITATION_2] . C3-HA mice were adoptively transferred with clone 4 CD8 + cells and given αLAG-3 injections at the time of transfer and 3 days later, with lungs being harvested on day 7. In contrast to untreated C3-HA mice, clone 4 CD8 + cells expanded significantly in lungs of mice treated with αLAG-3 ( Figure 1B ), and their IFN-γ production was greatly enhanced ( Figure 1C ). While the αLAG-3 antibody has been thought to block LAG-3 function, it is also possible that LAG-3 expression on CD8 + T cells is stimulatory and that the antibody acts as an agonist. Another question is whether the enhanced CD8 + accumulation and function upon in vivo αLAG-3 antibody treatment reflect functional effects on CD8 + T cells or are completely secondary to effects on endogenous CD4 + T cells (or other cells). In order to resolve these questions, we crossed the clone 4 TCR transgenic mice onto a LAG-3 -/-background. Similar to wild-type clone 4 CD8 + cells transferred into αLAG-3-treated mice, clone 4 LAG-3 -/-mice expanded and produced large amounts of IFN-γ ( Figure 1 , B and C). Cells from lungs were counted, and absolute numbers of clone 4 cells ( Figure 1D ) and IFN-γ-producing clone 4 cells ( Figure 1E ) were calculated. The",
